  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about cashback credit cards</p></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What is the maximum cashback I can earn per month?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most cashback credit cards have a monthly or quarterly cap on cashback earnings. For example, the SBI Cashback card caps cashback at ₹5,000 per statement cycle, while the HDFC Millennia limits 5% cashback to ₹1,000 per month on online spends. However, cards like Axis ACE and IndusInd Tiger offer relatively generous caps or no meaningful restrictions on flat cashback. Always check the card's terms for category-wise caps before applying to ensure the card suits your spending volume.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is cashback credited automatically to my account?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, for most cashback credit cards, the cashback is automatically credited as a statement credit in your next billing cycle. You don't need to manually redeem or claim anything. For example, if you earn ₹500 cashback in January, it will appear as a credit in your February statement, effectively reducing your outstanding balance. Some cards like ICICI Amazon Pay credit cashback as Amazon Pay balance instead of statement credit — so verify the cashback mechanism for your specific card.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Which is better — flat cashback or category cashback?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Flat cashback cards (like IndusInd Tiger at 1.5% on everything) are better for people with diverse spending across many categories, as you earn the same rate regardless of where you shop. Category cashback cards (like SBI Cashback at 5% online) are better if your spending is concentrated in specific categories — the higher rate on targeted categories yields more total cashback. If 70%+ of your spending falls in one category, choose a category card. Otherwise, a flat cashback card gives more predictable, hassle-free returns.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Do cashback cards have annual fees?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">It varies by card. Several excellent cashback cards are lifetime free — including Axis ACE, ICICI Amazon Pay, and IndusInd Tiger. Others like SBI Cashback (₹999/year) and HDFC Millennia (₹1,000/year) charge annual fees but often waive them when you meet a minimum annual spending threshold (typically ₹1-3 lakh). Before choosing a paid cashback card, calculate your expected annual cashback and subtract the fee to determine net savings. If a free card delivers comparable net returns, it's the smarter choice.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can I earn cashback on EMI transactions?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Generally, no. Most cashback credit cards exclude EMI-converted transactions, balance transfers, and cash advances from cashback eligibility. Cashback typically applies only to regular retail purchases made at POS terminals or online. Additionally, transactions at fuel stations, wallet loads, and insurance premium payments may also be excluded or earn reduced cashback. Always read the product terms sheet for the specific exclusion list. Some newer cards like Axis ACE have fewer exclusions, making them more generous for everyday use.</div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

